Linked List 

Introduction

A Linked List is a linear data structure consisting of nodes connected through pointers.

Each node contains:
Data
Pointer(s) to the next node (and previous node in doubly linked lists).
Unlike arrays, linked lists do not store elements in contiguous memory.
They are dynamic in size and allow efficient insertion and deletion.

Types of Linked Lists

1. Singly Linked List (SLL)
Each node contains data and a next pointer.
Traversal is possible only in the forward direction.

2. Circular Singly Linked List (CSLL)
Similar to a singly linked list.
The last node points back to the first node, forming a circular structure.

3. Doubly Linked List (DLL)
Each node contains:
Data
Previous pointer
Next pointer
Supports both forward and backward traversal.

4. Circular Doubly Linked List (CDLL)
Similar to a doubly linked list.
The last node points to the first node, and the first node points back to the last node.

Operations on Linked Lists

Traversal

Visit each node sequentially.
Time Complexity: O(n)

Searching

Search for an element by traversing the list.
Time Complexity: O(n)

Insertion

At the beginning: O(1)
At the end:
O(n) (without tail pointer)
O(1) (with tail pointer)
At a specific position: O(n)

Deletion

From the beginning: O(1)
From the end: O(n)
At a specific position: O(n)

Advantages

Dynamic size (grows and shrinks at runtime).
Efficient insertion and deletion.
Does not require contiguous memory.
Better memory utilization for dynamic data.

Disadvantages

No direct/random access to elements.
Searching is slower than arrays.
Extra memory is needed for pointers.
Sequential traversal increases access time.

Applications

Implementing Stacks and Queues.
Dynamic memory allocation.
Music playlists and image viewers.
Browser history navigation.
Undo/Redo operations in editors.